riers to Public Participation in Memorialization Processes: Evidence from the Dutch Holocaust Memorial of Names -- tChapter 9. Delisting Dresden: Bridging Local Interests and International Obligations -- tPart IV. Bottom-up Open Interactive Heritage Governance: Governing the Public Good and Common Pool Resources -- tChapter 10. White Lions in South Africa: A Living Heritage -- tPart V. Bottom-up Closed Interactive Heritage Governance: Governing Common Pool Resources -- tChapter 11. From Paradigm Shift to Practice: Experimenting Innovation in Participatory Heritage Making -- tChapter 12. Participation as an Effective Way to Stimulate Multivocality in Heritage Discourse? -- tConclusion -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThere is a call in Heritage Studies to democratize heritage practices and place local communities at the forefront; heritage plays an important role in identity formation, and therefore in social inclusion and exclusion. Public participation is often presented as the primary means to prioritize communities. Studies focusing on public participation are typically descriptive in nature, however these studies lack a strong analytical framework that enables us to understand participation. This series of studies contributes to a better understanding of public participation in the heritage sector by applying Public Administration theory on collaborative governance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aArchaeology and statevCase studies. 0aArt and statevCase studies. 0aCultural propertyxProtectionvCase studies. 0aCultural propertyxProtectionxCitizen participationvCase studies. 0aPublic administrationvCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aHeritage Studies, Cultural Studie